   <h2>
    Beautiful Chess
   </h2>
   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <b>
     <img alt="" height="200" src="data:image/png;base64," width="145"/>
     "Beautiful chess
    </b>
    is a
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess_variant" title="Chess variant">
     chess variant
    </a>
    originated by amateur players from
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Czech_Republic" title="Czech Republic">
     Czech Republic
    </a>
    in 2013. It is similar to
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess960" title="Chess960">
     Chess960
    </a>
    and
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcendental_chess" title="Transcendental chess">
     Transcendental chess
    </a>
    .
 In Beautiful chess the beginning positions of the pieces on the back 
row are changed, with an idea to preserve the spirit of the game and 
increase variability while retaining symmetry between pieces."
    <br/>
    Original Source: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beautiful_chess
    <div style="clear:both; padding-bottom:0.25em">
    </div>

   <h2>
    Squoval
   </h2>
   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <a href="http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=37135173" imageanchor="1" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
    </a>
    <br/>
    <div class="separator" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em; text-align: center;">
     <a href="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/aa/Squoval.jpg/220px-Squoval.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
     </a>
     <a href="http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=37135173" imageanchor="1" style="clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;">
     </a>
     <img border="0" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/aa/Squoval.jpg/220px-Squoval.jpg"/>
     <a href="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/aa/Squoval.jpg/220px-Squoval.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
     </a>
     <a href="http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=37135173" imageanchor="1" style="clear: right; float: right; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-left: 1em;">
     </a>
     <a href="http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=37135173" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
     </a>
    </div>
    <br/>
    <a href="http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=37135173" imageanchor="1" style="clear: left; float: left; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 1em;">
    </a>
    <i>
     <b>
      Squoval
     </b>
    </i>
    is a
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portmanteau" title="Portmanteau">
     portmanteau
    </a>
    of the terms and shapes "square" and "oval." The word can refer to the not quite
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oval" title="Oval">
     oval
    </a>
    , not quite
    <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_%28geometry%29" title="Square (geometry)">
     square
    </a>
    shape of a
    <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fingernail" title="Fingernail">
     fingernail
    </a>
    or
    <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toenail" title="Toenail">
     toenail
    </a>
    .
    <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1">
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Squoval#cite_note-1">
     </a>
    </sup>
    "Essentially a conservative square with the length of a square nail but
 the softer edges of an oval" the term was coined to refer to fingernail
 shape in 1984 by Paula Gilmore, a prominent stylist and educator, 
according to Peters.
    <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Crowley_2-0">
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Squoval#cite_note-Crowley-2">
     </a>
    </sup>
    This style was popular in the 1990s, and is still a popular natural nail shape. This article is licensed under the
    <a href="http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/fdl.html">
     GNU Free Documentation License
    </a>
    .
    <br/>
    <br/>
    Source:

    </a>

   <h2>
    Water Retention on Mathematical Surfaces
   </h2>
   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-Xgtmg2QlRGQ/TudYLPcB4FI/AAAAAAAAAqU/QvslY5Cak-A/s1600/Wateronsurface.png" onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}">
     <img alt="" border="0" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5685610004724441170" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-Xgtmg2QlRGQ/TudYLPcB4FI/AAAAAAAAAqU/QvslY5Cak-A/s320/Wateronsurface.png" style="cursor: hand; cursor: pointer; float: left; height: 209px; margin: 0 10px 10px 0; width: 320px;"/>
    </a>
    <br/>
    This article concerns the mathematical problem of finding the maximum  retention of water on various surfaces. Imagine a surface of cells of  various heights on a regular array such as a square lattice, and water  is rained down on every cell in the system. The boundaries of the system  are open and allow water to flow out. Water will be trapped in ponds,  and eventually all ponds will fill to their maximum height, with any  additional water flowing over spillways and out the boundaries of the  system. The problem is to find the amount of water trapped or retained  for a given surface.
    <br/>
    <br/>
    This has been studied extensively for two  mathematical surfaces: (1) Magic Square and (2) Random Surfaces (discussed in this entry).   In 2010, water retention on magic squares was used as a challenge in Al Zimmermann contest: find the L x L
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magic_square" title="Magic square">
     magic square
    </a>
    with the maximum water retention. This article is licensed under the
    <a href="http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/fdl.html">
     GNU Free Documentation License
    </a>
    . It uses material from the
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Water_retention_on_mathematical_surfaces">
     Wikipedia article "Water retention on mathematical surfaces"
    </a>
    .  This entry is a fragment of a larger work. Link may die if entry is finally removed or merged.
    <div style="clear:both; padding-bottom:0.25em">
    </div>
    <br/>

   <h2>
    Ashkenazi Intelligence
   </h2>
   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-l9coIbIgGYA/Tkk3QzLi4GI/AAAAAAAAAqM/Px1TEvZig-c/s1600/jewish_star.jpg" onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}">
     <img alt="" border="0" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5641100770014322786" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-l9coIbIgGYA/Tkk3QzLi4GI/AAAAAAAAAqM/Px1TEvZig-c/s320/jewish_star.jpg" style="float:left; margin:0 10px 10px 0;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 320px; height: 240px;"/>
    </a>
    <br/>
    The
    <b>
     intelligence of Ashkenazi Jews
    </b>
    has been the subject of study and speculation within the fields of
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychometry" title="Psychometry">
     psychometry
    </a>
    and
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolutionary_biology" title="Evolutionary biology">
     evolutionary biology
    </a>
    . Psychometric studies have reported a higher than average
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intelligence_quotient" title="Intelligence quotient">
     intelligence quotient
    </a>
    among
    <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashkenazi" title="Ashkenazi">
     Ashkenazi
    </a>
    Jews than among the general population. There has been a broad range of  speculation about the possible causes of these findings, as well as a  measure of controversy, as they touch upon several sensitive subjects  such as the possible relationship between
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Race_and_intelligence" title="Race and intelligence">
     race and intelligence
    </a>
    , as well as issues of
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Racialism" title="Racialism">
     racialism
    </a>
    ,
    <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philo-semitism" title="Philo-semitism">
     philo-semitism
    </a>
    and
    <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-semitism" title="Anti-semitism">
     anti-semitism
    </a>
    . One highly publicised proposal by
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gregory_Cochran" title="Gregory Cochran">
     Gregory Cochran
    </a>
    , Jason Hardy and
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Harpending" title="Henry Harpending">
     Henry Harpending
    </a>
    ,  suggests that the Ashkenazi had jobs in which increased IQ strongly  favoured economic success, in contrast with other populations, who were  mostly peasant farmers.
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashkenazi_intelligence#cite_note-cochranetal-1">
     <span>
     </span>
    </a>

    <a href="http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/fdl.html">
     GNU Free Documentation License
    </a>
    . It uses material from the
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashkenazi_intelligence">
     Wikipedia article "Ashkenazi Intelligence"
    </a>
    .  This entry is a fragment of a larger work. Link may die if entry is finally removed or merged.
    <br/>
    <div style="clear:both; padding-bottom:0.25em">
    </div>
    <br/>
    <div class="byline">
     <a href="http://wikidumper.blogspot.com/2011/08/ashkenazi-intelligence.html" title="permanent link">
      #
     </a>
     posted by Cliff Pickover @ 8:06 AM
     <a href="https://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=37135173&amp;postID=3283658138181520417" location.href="https://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=37135173&amp;postID=3283658138181520417;">
      1 comments

    <br/>
    <b>
     Soft salad
    </b>
    <span style="font-weight: normal;">
     (
     <i>
      sofuto sarada
     </i>
     )
    </span>
    is a salty, dry Japanese rice cracker
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snack_food" title="Snack food">
     snack food
    </a>
    trademarked by
    <a class="new" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Kameda_Seika&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" title="Kameda Seika (page does not exist)">
     Kameda Seika
    </a>
    . The name derives from the fact that it is softer than traditional
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Senbei" title="Senbei">
     senbei
    </a>
    , and that salad-yu
    <span style="font-weight: normal;">
     (
     <i>
      sarada-yu
     </i>
     , Japanese for
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vegetable_oil" title="Vegetable oil">
      vegetable oil
     </a>
     )
    </span>
    is used in the manufacturing process. The company decided to use the  term "salad-flavored" rather than "salt-flavored (shio-aji)" in order to  have a more fashionable, western-sounding name. However, since the name is confusing, the name is often unofficially appended as
    <b>
     soft salad senbei

   </h2>
   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/S8O1_-ImwMI/AAAAAAAAAow/NhOB719g9g0/s1600/bassg.jpg" onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}">
     <img alt="" border="0" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5459407283918651586" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/S8O1_-ImwMI/AAAAAAAAAow/NhOB719g9g0/s320/bassg.jpg" style="float: left; margin: 0pt 10px 10px 0pt; cursor: pointer; width: 91px; height: 150px;"/>
    </a>
    The Spider Chord is a guitar technique popularized during the 80s
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thrash_metal" title="Thrash metal">
     thrash  metal
    </a>
    scene. Although its origins are unknown, it is widely  regarded as being invented by
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dave_Mustaine" title="Dave Mustaine">
     Dave  Mustaine
    </a>
    of
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Megadeth" title="Megadeth">
     Megadeth
    </a>
    , although
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerry_King" title="Kerry King">
     Kerry  King
    </a>
    has also claimed he was the first to use it. It is used to  reduce string noise when playing (mostly chromatic) riffs which require  chords across several strings.The Spider Chord requires the player to use all four fingers. Two  fingers will be fret 5th while the other fret another 5th. This  technique then allows you to run down the neck playing either of the two  chords. This article is licensed under the

   <h2>
    UFOs and the Bible
   </h2>
   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/S3tAY5wXe2I/AAAAAAAAAog/J1XZQXQssaM/s1600-h/braina.jpg" onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}">
     <img alt="" border="0" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5439011771544730466" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/S3tAY5wXe2I/AAAAAAAAAog/J1XZQXQssaM/s320/braina.jpg" style="margin: 0pt 10px 10px 0pt; float: left; cursor: pointer; width: 160px; height: 146px;"/>
    </a>
    <br/>
    The advent of the phenomenon of Unidentified Flying Objects (UFOs) in the middle of the 20th Century has led to a wide range of religious speculation, especially in regard to the Bible, in western culture. There have been four major theories put forward to connect UFOs and the Bible: the ancient astronaut, the angelic, the demonic, and the fallen angel theory. These theories all seek to reconcile the concept of extraterrestrial visitation with the biblical material. There is also a wider sense in which UFOs have influenced religious imagination, and in this regard the Bible is seen as a resource but not as an authority to be interpreted. There are three other major ways in which the issue of religious imagination has related to the UFO experience: UFOs as a modern religious mythology, UFOs as hope for a New Age spirituality, and the emergence of religious cults rooted in UFO mythology.
    <p>
     All of this discussion has taken place against a back drop in which the governments of the world deny that we are being visited by an extraterrestrial reality, while UFO researchers claim that the evidence of a cover-up is overwhelming. The United States Air Force study of UFOs stated there was no factual basis whatever of a government UFO cover-up.
     <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-0">
      <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UFOs_and_the_Bible#cite_note-0">
       <span>
       </span>
       <span>
       </span>
      </a>
     </sup>
    </p>
    <p>
     But authors such as Donald Keyhoe, Timothy Good, Richard M. Dolan, Terry Hansen, Lawrence Fawcett and Barry J. Greenwood believe there is a cover-up.
     <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1">
      <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UFOs_and_the_Bible#cite_note-1">
       <span>
       </span>
      </a>
     </sup>
     Because of the lack of clarity about UFO truth, a truly scientific and academic appraisal of the religious implications of UFOs can only be tentative at this time. This article is licensed under the
     <a href="http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/fdl.html">
      GNU Free Documentation License
     </a>
     . It uses material from the
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UFOs_and_the_Bible">
      Wikipedia article "UFOs and the Bible"
     </a>
     .  This entry is a fragment of a larger work. Link may die if entry is finally removed or merged.
     <br/>
    </p>

   <h2>
    Instant Rice
   </h2>
   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/SvChEha-3lI/AAAAAAAAAoE/SHDSDN3gQV8/s1600-h/minuterice.jpg">
     <img alt="" border="0" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5399993052280315474" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/SvChEha-3lI/AAAAAAAAAoE/SHDSDN3gQV8/s320/minuterice.jpg" style="FLOAT: left; MARGIN: 0px 10px 10px 0px; WIDTH: 166px; CURSOR: hand; HEIGHT: 250px"/>
    </a>
    <br/>
    <div>
     Instant rice, also known as minute rice, is
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rice" title="Rice">
      rice
     </a>
     that has been precooked and
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dehydrated" title="Dehydrated">
      dehydrated
     </a>
     so that it cooks more rapidly. Regular rice requires approximately 20 minutes to cook while instant rice needs anywhere between five and 10 minutes. Because it has already been cooked, all that is necessary to prepare instant rice is to simply re-hydrate it with hot water. nstant rice is made by using several methods. The most common method is similar to the home cooking process. The rice is blanched in hot water, steamed and rinsed. It is then placed in large
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oven" title="Oven">
      ovens
     </a>
     for dehydration until the moisture content reaches approximately twelve percent or less.
    </div>
    <div>
     <br/>
     The basic principle involves increasing moisture of the milled white rice by using steam or water to form cracks or holes in the kernels. The fast cooking properties come from the fact that, when recooked, water can penetrate into the cracked grain much more quickly.
     <br/>

      Wikipedia article "Instant Rice"
     </a>

   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/SpF2Q08yVrI/AAAAAAAAAmM/qPvOXqWKJhU/s1600-h/chair.jpg">
     <img alt="" border="0" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5373205861893297842" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/SpF2Q08yVrI/AAAAAAAAAmM/qPvOXqWKJhU/s320/chair.jpg" style="MARGIN: 0px 10px 10px 0px; WIDTH: 240px; FLOAT: left; HEIGHT: 240px; CURSOR: hand"/>
    </a>
    <br/>
    <div>
     The polypropylene stacking chair is a chair manufactured in an injection moulding process using polypropylene. It was designed by Robin Day in 1963 for S.Hille &amp; Co.
     <br/>
     <br/>
     This is one of the very few chairs that after over 40 years is still in production and has been been made in forty countries around the world, for schools, hospitals, airports, canteens, restaurants, arenas, hotels, as well as homes.[1] It is the best-selling chair in the world.[2]
     <br/>
     <br/>
     The chair first appeared on the market in a choice of charcoal or flame red colours at a little under 3 in price. The side chair won a Council of Industrial Design (now the Design Council) award in 1965.
     <br/>
     <br/>
     The brief from Hille was for a low cost mass-produced stacking chair, affordable by all and to meet virtually every seating requirement. Over time it became available in a wide variety of colours and with different forms of base and upholstery. These variations have included Series E for children, made in five sizes with lifting holes, and Polo with rows of graduated circular holes making it suitable for outdoor use.
     <br/>
     <br/>
     The one-piece seat and back was injection moulded from polypropylene, a lightweight thermoplastic with a high impact resistance. It was invented by an Italian scientist, Guilio Natta, in 1954. This article is licensed under the

   <h2>
    Pip's Three-Handed Chess
   </h2>
   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <a href="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/SmZwaXy8LsI/AAAAAAAAAlc/p1WC-RLJLcs/s1600-h/chess.jpg" onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}">
     <img alt="" border="0" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5361096004797738690" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/SmZwaXy8LsI/AAAAAAAAAlc/p1WC-RLJLcs/s320/chess.jpg" style="margin: 0pt 10px 10px 0pt; float: left; cursor: pointer; width: 299px; height: 320px;"/>
    </a>
    <br/>
    Pip's Three-Handed Chess is a
    <a href="http://www.blogger.com/wiki/Chess_variant" title="Chess variant">
     chess variant
    </a>
    for three players played using a  standard square chess board. It is played as a series of at least two games, in  which the winner is the first player to mate each opponent in a game.
    <p>
     Standard chess rules apply, with the following exceptions or  clarifications:
    </p>
    <ul>
     <li>
      Pawns must go forward in the direction they originally face.
     </li>
     <li>
      Castling is not allowed.
     </li>
     <li>
      Pawns only move one space at a time.
     </li>
     <li>
      Match ends when a player checkmates each of his opponents. Games are reset  after each checkmate.
     </li>
     <li>
      Checkmate is official on the mated players turn, not when it is first made  (if there is a player between the player mating and the player being mated, he  may choose to "unmate" the player).
     </li>
     <li>
      Players alternate the order of turns each game, starting clockwise.
     </li>
     <li>
      Players rotate board sides each game clockwise.
     </li>
     <li>
      If a player puts an opponent in checkmate, then another opponent puts the  same player in checkmate (either a different checkmate or "adding to" the  checkmate), then the first player to put the opponent in checkmate gets credit  for the win.
     </li>
    </ul>

    </div>
    <a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/SjEYHEWgaOI/AAAAAAAAAlM/76O2enPaNbw/s1600-h/bacon.jpg">
     <img alt="" border="0" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5346080742371780834" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/SjEYHEWgaOI/AAAAAAAAAlM/76O2enPaNbw/s320/bacon.jpg" style="FLOAT: left; MARGIN: 0px 10px 10px 0px; WIDTH: 254px; CURSOR: hand; HEIGHT: 198px"/>

    <br/>
    <div>
     A bacon egg and cheese sandwich is a
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breakfast_sandwich" title="Breakfast sandwich">
      Breakfast sandwich
     </a>
     made with
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bacon" title="Bacon">
      bacon
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egg" title="Egg">
      eggs
     </a>
     (typically
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fried_egg" title="Fried egg">
      fried
     </a>
     or
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scrambled_eggs" title="Scrambled eggs">
      scrambled
     </a>
     ),
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cheese" title="Cheese">
      cheese
     </a>
     and some type of
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bread" title="Bread">
      bread
     </a>
      a
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hard_roll" title="Hard roll">

     </a>
     , typically  which is usually
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Butter" title="Butter">
      buttered
     </a>

     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toast" title="Toast">

     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sandwich" title="Sandwich">

     </a>
     substitute
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sausage" title="Sausage">

     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ham" title="Ham">
      ham
     </a>

     <br/>
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonic_Drive-In" title="Sonic Drive-In">

     </a>

     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arby%E2%80%99s" title="Arbys">

Burger King serves up a Croissanwich with Bacon, Egg &amp; Cheese (360 calories and 22 grams of fat) as well as a Double Croissanwich with Sausage, Bacon, Egg &amp; Cheese (610 calories and 46 grams of fat).In New Zealand and some parts of Australia a "Massive McMuffin" is offered with ketchup, bacon, egg, American cheese and two sausage patties.

     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acronym" title="Acronym">

     for the sandwich as is 
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BE%26C" title="BE&amp;C">

   <h2>
    Slow Sex Movement
   </h2>
   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/Shnib_AZPOI/AAAAAAAAAkE/ODB6ea3vDbg/s1600-h/cherie.jpg">
     <img alt="" border="0" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5339547803621866722" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/Shnib_AZPOI/AAAAAAAAAkE/ODB6ea3vDbg/s320/cherie.jpg" style="FLOAT: left; MARGIN: 0px 10px 10px 0px; WIDTH: 91px; CURSOR: hand; HEIGHT: 82px"/>
    </a>
    <br/>
    <div>
     Slow Sex Movement (as a
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_movement" title="Social movement">
      social movement
     </a>
     ) has emerged in early 2009 and borrows from a long
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tradition" title="Tradition">
      tradition
     </a>
     spanning many centuries, several
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cultures" title="Cultures">
      cultures
     </a>
     and many
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belief_systems" title="Belief systems">
      belief systems
     </a>
     , including
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tantra" title="Tantra">
      Tantra
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoga" title="Yoga">
      Yoga
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddhism" title="Buddhism">
      Buddhism
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddhist_meditation" title="Buddhist meditation">
      Buddhist meditation
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taoism" title="Taoism">
      Taoism
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qigong" title="Qigong">
      qigong
     </a>
     , and integrates
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eastern_medicine" title="Eastern medicine">
      Eastern medicine
     </a>
     and
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_medicine" title="Western medicine">
      Western medicine
     </a>
     going back to
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippocrates" title="Hippocrates">
      Hippocrates
     </a>
     , theories of
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilhelm_Reich" title="Wilhelm Reich">
      Wilhelm Reich
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orgasm" title="Orgasm">
      orgasm
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology" title="Biology">
      biology
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sociobiology" title="Sociobiology">
      sociobiology
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biological_psychiatry" title="Biological psychiatry">
      biological psychiatry
     </a>
     and
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolutionary_theory" title="Evolutionary theory">
      evolutionary theory
     </a>
     .
     <br/>
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orgasmic_Meditation" title="Orgasmic Meditation">
      Orgasmic Meditation
     </a>
     and
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mindful" title="Mindful">
      mindful
     </a>
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sexuality" title="Sexuality">
      sexuality
     </a>
     generally are referred to as a practices of the "
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slow_sex" title="Slow sex">
      slow sex
     </a>
     "
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Movement" title="Movement">
      movement
     </a>
     and have been compared with the "
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slow_food" title="Slow food">
      slow food
     </a>
     " movement as popularized by chef
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_Waters" title="Alice Waters">
      Alice Waters
     </a>
     (founded by Carlo Petrini in Italy), in that comparison both strip away the trappings and conventions that have developed around a
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental" title="Fundamental">
      fundamental
     </a>
     human activity in order to rediscover their raw
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biological" title="Biological">
      biological
     </a>
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Essence" title="Essence">
      essence
     </a>
     while observing
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Safer_Sex" title="Safer Sex">
      Safer Sex
     </a>
     practices and to increase both
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pleasure" title="Pleasure">
      pleasure
     </a>
     and
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Healthfulness" title="Healthfulness">
      healthfulness
     </a>
     .
     <br/>
     The Slow Sex
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Movement" title="Movement">
      Movement
     </a>
     is said to diverge from the consumerism and productivity nature of sexuality and relationships of the 20th Century and brings awareness to the
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intimacy" title="Intimacy">
      intimacy
     </a>
     and connections needs of all humans.
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orgasmic_Meditation" title="Orgasmic Meditation">
      Orgasmic Meditation
     </a>
     as languaged by William Safire in the New York Times
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slow_Sex_Movement#cite_note-New_York_Times:_.5B.5BOrgasmic_Meditation.5D.5D-1" title="">
      [2]
     </a>
     , referencing the earlier Times article on mindful sexuality
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slow_Sex_Movement#cite_note-New_York_Times:_Pleasure_Principle-0" title="">
      [1]
     </a>
     . Proponents reference reawakening through
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mindful" title="Mindful">
      mindful
     </a>
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sexuality" title="Sexuality">
      sexuality
     </a>
     and training ones senses through a practice of
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orgasmic_Meditation" title="Orgasmic Meditation">
      Orgasmic Meditation
     </a>
     partners rediscover the joys of sensation and learn to stay present through intense
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sensations" title="Sensations">
      sensations
     </a>
     in their
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daily_life" title="Daily life">
      daily life
     </a>
     . This article is licensed under the
     <a href="http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/fdl.html">
      GNU Free Documentation License
     </a>
     . It uses material from the
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slow_Sex_Movement">
      Wikipedia article "Slow Sex Movement"
     </a>
     . This entry is a fragment of a larger work. Link may die if entry is finally removed or merged.
    </div>

    </div>

   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <a href="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/ScLgqwso-DI/AAAAAAAAAi8/YMAOg5IHHZc/s1600-h/archi.jpg">
     <img alt="" border="0" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5315057535481870386" src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/ScLgqwso-DI/AAAAAAAAAi8/YMAOg5IHHZc/s320/archi.jpg" style="FLOAT: left; MARGIN: 0px 10px 10px 0px; WIDTH: 89px; CURSOR: hand; HEIGHT: 98px"/>
    </a>
    <br/>
    <div>
     A Zuckerman number is an
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title="Integer">
      integer
     </a>
     that is divisible by the product of its digits in a given
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numeral_system" title="Numeral system">
      number base
     </a>
     . All integers between 1 and the base number are Zuckerman numbers. No integer with a zero as one or more of its digits in base b can be a Zuckerman number in that base. In base 10, the first few Zuckerman numbers with more than one digit are
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/11_%28number%29" title="11 (number)">
      11
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/12_%28number%29" title="12 (number)">
      12
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/15_%28number%29" title="15 (number)">
      15
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/24_%28number%29" title="24 (number)">
      24
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/36_%28number%29" title="36 (number)">
      36
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/111_%28number%29" title="111 (number)">
      111
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/112_%28number%29" title="112 (number)">
      112
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/115_%28number%29" title="115 (number)">
      115
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/128_%28number%29" title="128 (number)">
      128
     </a>
     , 132, 135,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/144_%28number%29" title="144 (number)">
      144
     </a>
     , 175, 212, 216, 224, 312, 315, 384. This article is licensed under the
     <a href="http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/fdl.html">
      GNU Free Documentation License

    </a>
    <br/>
    <div>
     The Extra-Terrestrial Exposure Law (14 C.F.R. 1211 of the Code of Federal Regulations) was the popular name for a United States administrative regulation promulgated in 1969 to prevent the spread of biological contamination from space. Implemented before the Apollo 11 mission, it provided the legal authority for a quarantine period for the returning astronauts. The regulation included a definition of exposure as "the state of condition of any person, property, animal or other form of life or matter whatever, who or which has touched directly or come within the atmospheric envelope or any other celestial body or touched directly or been in close proximity (or exposed indirectly to) any person, property, animal or other form of life or matter who or which has been extraterrestrially exposed by virtue of paragraph (b)(1) of this section."    </h2>
   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/SKXoPV9wKmI/AAAAAAAAAU4/GVVXfnwNa5w/s1600-h/usb-bladder.jpg">
     <img alt="" border="0" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5234845492179905122" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/SKXoPV9wKmI/AAAAAAAAAU4/GVVXfnwNa5w/s320/usb-bladder.jpg" style="FLOAT: left; MARGIN: 0px 10px 10px 0px; CURSOR: hand"/>
    </a>
    <br/>
    <div>
     The World's Most Phallic Building contest was a contest held in 2003 by
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cabinet_magazine" title="Cabinet magazine">
      Cabinet magazine
     </a>
     to find the building which most resembled a
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human" title="Human">
      human
     </a>
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phallus" title="Phallus">
      phallus
     </a>
     .The contest originated when writer
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonathan_Ames" title="Jonathan Ames">
      Jonathan Ames
     </a>
     drew the ire of
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slate_%28magazine%29" title="Slate (magazine)">
      Slate
     </a>
     readers by claiming, in a diary later published in his book I Love You More Than You Know, that the
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Williamsburgh_Savings_Bank_Tower" title="Williamsburgh Savings Bank Tower">
      Williamsburg Bank Building
     </a>
     in
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brooklyn" title="Brooklyn">
      Brooklyn
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">
      New York City
     </a>
     ,
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York" title="New York">
      New York
     </a>
     , was the world's most phallic, leading Cabinet magazine to initiate a search of its own to find which building was truly the "world's most phallic." Cities and readers subsequently poured in their views and staked their claims to the magazine's editors. After months of entries and discussion, the
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ypsilanti_Water_Tower" title="Ypsilanti Water Tower">
      Ypsilanti Water Tower
     </a>
     was announced as the winner, although the winner of a readers' poll was the
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Florida_State_Capitol" title="Florida State Capitol">
      Florida State Capitol
     </a>
     building in
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tallahassee" title="Tallahassee">
      Tallahassee
     </a>
     . Another notable nominee was the
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torre_Agbar" title="Torre Agbar">
      Torre Agbar
     </a>
     (Agbar Tower) in
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barcelona" title="Barcelona">
      Barcelona
     </a>

   <h2>
    Historical Christian Hairstyles
   </h2>
   <div class="blogPost">
    <div style="clear:both;">
    </div>
    <a href="http://bp0.blogger.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/SHv2kMmf6NI/AAAAAAAAAUg/UMhWKGzxHW8/s1600-h/god-lamb.jpg">
     <img alt="" border="0" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5223039294584645842" src="http://bp0.blogger.com/_Vx9S83U2e6A/SHv2kMmf6NI/AAAAAAAAAUg/UMhWKGzxHW8/s320/god-lamb.jpg" style="FLOAT: left; MARGIN: 0px 10px 10px 0px; CURSOR: hand"/>
    </a>
    <br/>
    <div>
     The paintings in the
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catacombs" title="Catacombs">
      catacombs
     </a>
     permit the belief that the early Christians simply followed the fashion of their time. The short hair of the men and the waved tresses of the women were, towards the end of the second century, curled, frizzed with irons, and arranged in tiers, while for women the hair twined about the head forming a high
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diadem" title="Diadem">
      diadem
     </a>
     over the brow. Particular locks were reserved to fall over the forehead and upon the temples.
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_iconography" title="Christian iconography">
      Christian iconography
     </a>
     still proceeds in accordance with types created in the beginning of Christianity. Images of Christ retain the long hair parted in the middle and flowing to the shoulders. Those of the
     <a class="mw-redirect" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blessed_Virgin" title="Blessed Virgin">
      Blessed Virgin
     </a>
     still wear the veil which conceals a portion of the brow and confines the neck. This article is licensed under the
     <a href="http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/fdl.html">
      GNU Free Documentation License
     </a>
     . It uses material from the
     <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Historical_Christian_hairstyles">
      Wikipedia article "Historical Christian Hairstyles"
     </a>
     . This entry is a fragment of a larger work. Link may die if entry is finally removed or merged.
    </div>
